    rectoEn: 'The convergence trade: definition, LTCM\'s canonical example, and the weakness inside the definition itself?',
    versoEn: 'Buy a discounted asset, short its overpriced twin, WAIT for the gap to close — the gain does not depend on market direction, only on convergence. The canonical example: the off-the-run Treasury (old issue, less liquid) yields a few bp more than the on-the-run, for identical credit risk — buy one, sell the other. Each position earns very little, hence massive leverage. The weakness lies in the word "wait": the gap can WIDEN for a long time before closing, and you must be able to hold. The anchor: LTCM\'s trades almost all converged… in 1999, after the fund\'s death.',
