    rectoEn: 'The Nasdaq: peak, trough, length of the fall, recovery — the four numbers?',
    versoEn: 'PEAK: 5,048.62 on MARCH 10, 2000, with an index P/E above 100 (versus a 15-20 historical average). TROUGH: 1,114.11 on OCTOBER 9, 2002 — that is −77.9%, over 31 MONTHS of erosion, without a single crash day, with 20% rebounds ruining the "buy the dip" crowd. RECOVERY: 5,000 is only seen again in APRIL 2015 — fifteen years. The anchor: the burst destroys ~$5,000bn of market cap — and causes NO banking crisis: the losses were held unlevered, in cash accounts. Compare with chapter 5.',
